rn Irish: variant of   Lundy  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Lunde  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lundy","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: habitational name from any of several places called Lundie, for example one near Doune in Perthshire.","Irish: topographic name from Anglo-Norman French <i>de la Launde</i> ‘of the glade’. Compare   Lown   1.","Americanized form of Norwegian   Lunde  ."]}]},{"name":"Malcolm","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval Gaelic name <i>Mael Coluim</i> ‘devotee of St Columba’. Columba was a 6th-century monk of Irish origin who played a leading part in the conversion to Christianity of Scotland and northern England;  see also  Callum   and   Colm .  He has always been one of the most popular saints in Scotland, but in the Middle Ages it was felt to be presumptuous to give the names of saints directly to children; instead their blessing was invoked by prefixing the name with <i>mael</i> ‘devotee of’ or <i>gille</i> ‘servant of’. Since the 1930s the given name has been used widely in the English-speaking world, not just by those with Scottish connections."],"variants":[]},{"name":"\"Máel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Fanciful spelling of   Gail  , also occasionally written  <b>Gaelle</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gail","meanings":["Shortened form of   Abigail .  It was not found as an independent given name before the middle of the 20th century; it became popular in the 1950s and 1960s, but has since fallen out of fashion."]}]},{"name":"Coluim\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Colm ."],"variants":[{"name":"Colm","meanings":["Traditional Irish form of the Late Latin personal name <i>Columba</i> ‘dove’.  See  <b>Callum</b>   ."]}